title: For Sale:  KelTec Sub9 (Glock Mags)
postcontent: 1998 Kel-Tec Sub-9 (accepts Glock mags) This is the Metal-framed predecessor to the KelTec Sub2000. More info on the Sub9: •KelTec says there were approximately 3500 made, with one of 10 different magazine/caliber combinations. •The receiver is machined from billet aluminum, and matching assembly numbers applied to the inside of both halves. •The feature-set was similar to that of the Colt R6450 (pistol caliber, adjustable front sight, last-round bolt hold-open), but also featured: forward assist (reciprocating bolt handle), interchangeable magwells to share magazines with your sidearm, and was collapsible for storage. •Optional accessories included a quick-detach scope base, built-in weapon light, laser, etc. •In 2000, the rifle was redesigned to reduce costs by: simplifying the firing assembly, removing the last-round bolt hold-open, and forming the receiver and barrel block out of polymer. It was also renamed Sub-2000. •In 2015, the rifle was redesigned again to speed up production. The polymer type, barrel (now threaded), and front sight were changed. It also got a facelift and mounting points for optics and accessories. It still carries the Sub-2000 name, but with the "Gen2" moniker. •It can be extrapolated that there were approximately 500 Glock 17 Sub-9s made based on magazine availability at the time, but it may be less. KelTec did not keep aggregated production data based on the magwells because they were intended to be "exchangeable" over the lifetime of the product. If you've wanted a Gen2 Sub 2000, then you'll love the Sub9 for it's feel, build, shootability, and scarcity. If you have any other questions, let me know.
